Mr Nixon was questioned about the 1970s political scandal that resulted from the break-in of the Democratic National Committee headquarters at the Watergate office complex in Washington D.C.

The scandal caused him to leave office in August 1974 and he remains the only U.S. president to resign. It also resulted in the indictment, trial, conviction and jailing of some of his top officials.

U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth ruled that special circumstances, especially the undisputed historical interest in Mr Nixon's testimony, far outweighed the need to keep the records secret.

‘Watergate significance in American history cannot be overstated,’ Judge Lamberth wrote.

